This project studies what happens when self-interested pricing algorithms repeatedly interact in a market: do they learn to compete and price down toward marginal cost, or do they learn to tacitly collude and raise prices toward the level a monopolist would charge, without ever communicating? The setting is a differentiated Bertrand duopoly, two firms selling similar but not identical products, each choosing a price every period. Demand follows a logit system, where the quantity a firm sells depends on its own price relative to its rival's price and to the value of not buying at all. Specifically, a firm's demand is the exponential of its quality-adjusted price divided by a temperature parameter, normalised by the same expression summed across both firms plus an outside option. The temperature parameter controls horizontal differentiation: as it approaches zero the products become perfect substitutes and the model collapses to homogeneous Bertrand competition, while larger values mean more product differentiation and therefore more pricing power for each firm. Each firm's profit in a period is its price-cost margin multiplied by the quantity it sells.

In a one-shot version of this game, each firm chooses a price to maximise its own profit taking the rival's price as fixed. This best-response condition, applied to both firms simultaneously, defines the Bertrand-Nash equilibrium: a pair of prices from which neither firm can profitably deviate on its own. Because each firm only internalises the effect of its price on its own profit and ignores the negative effect a price cut imposes on its rival, the Nash prices are low and profits are modest. This is the competitive benchmark. If instead the two firms were to coordinate and set prices jointly to maximise their combined profit, they would behave like a single monopolist running both products and would set a higher common price, earning higher profits each. This is the collusive or monopoly benchmark. The gap between these two outcomes is the entire object of interest: Nash represents competition, monopoly represents perfect collusion, and any realised outcome can be placed on a scale between them.

That placement is made precise by the collusion index, defined as the realised profit minus the Nash profit, divided by the monopoly profit minus the Nash profit. A value of zero means firms are earning exactly the competitive profit, a value of one means they are earning the full collusive profit, and intermediate values measure how far an outcome has drifted from competition toward collusion. The same normalisation can be applied to prices rather than profits. This single number is what makes it possible to detect collusion: rather than asking the unanswerable question of whether two algorithms have secretly agreed to fix prices, one simply measures where on the competition-to-collusion spectrum their behaviour actually lands.

The reason collusion is even a possibility, despite each firm being purely self-interested, is that the firms interact repeatedly rather than once. In a single encounter, undercutting a rival who is charging a high price is always profitable, so cooperation cannot survive and prices fall to the competitive level. But when the same firms meet period after period, a firm contemplating a price cut must weigh the immediate gain from undercutting against the future losses it will suffer once the rival retaliates by also cutting prices. If firms value the future sufficiently, the threat of retaliation can make sustained high prices an equilibrium of the repeated game. This is the logic of the folk theorem: a wide range of cooperative outcomes, including near-monopoly pricing, can be sustained as equilibria of an infinitely repeated game through strategies that reward cooperation and punish defection. Tacit collusion is therefore not a violation of self-interest; it is self-interest operating across time.

The classic embodiment of this idea is the strategy Tit-for-Tat, which emerged as the winner of Axelrod's tournaments on the repeated prisoner's dilemma. Tit-for-Tat cooperates on the first move and thereafter simply copies whatever its opponent did in the previous round. It is nice in that it is never the first to defect, retaliating in that it immediately punishes a defection, forgiving in that it returns to cooperation as soon as the opponent does, and clear in that its behaviour is easy for an opponent to understand and therefore to cooperate with. These four properties make it remarkably robust in repeated play. Translated into a pricing setting, a Tit-for-Tat firm starts by charging the cooperative high price and then mirrors its rival's most recent price, so that a rival who keeps prices high is rewarded with continued high prices while a rival who undercuts is met with an equally low price. Such a strategy can sustain collusion against a cooperative partner while remaining protected against exploitation.

Before any learning algorithm is introduced, the behaviour of fixed, rule-based strategies establishes what the various outcomes look like. A firm that always plays the Nash price represents relentless competition. A firm that always plays the monopoly price represents naive, unconditional cooperation, which is jointly profitable when matched against another cooperator but is exploitable: a self-interested rival facing an unconditional cooperator can undercut it and capture a large share of the market, pushing its own profit above the collusive level while the cooperator's profit collapses below the competitive level. A random-pricing firm provides a noise benchmark, and Tit-for-Tat provides conditional cooperation. Running these strategies against one another in repeated matches reveals the central tension cleanly: mutual cooperation is jointly best but individually fragile, unconditional cooperation is dangerous, and conditional cooperation backed by the threat of retaliation is what allows high prices to survive. These rule-based outcomes also serve a practical purpose, because they give a learning agent a meaningful set of benchmarks to be measured against; without them there would be no way to judge whether a learning agent had discovered anything beyond noise.

The learning agent itself is built on Q-learning, a reinforcement-learning method in which an agent learns the long-run value of taking each possible action in each possible situation purely from experience, without being told the rules of the market in advance. The agent maintains an estimate, called a Q-value, of the total discounted future reward it expects from choosing a given price in a given state, where the state summarises the relevant recent history of the market, in the simplest case the prices charged in the previous period. After each period the agent observes the profit it earned and the new state, and updates its estimate by nudging it toward the reward just received plus the discounted value of the best action available in the new state. This update embodies the Bellman principle, that the value of a decision is the immediate reward plus the discounted value of behaving optimally thereafter. The size of each adjustment is governed by a learning rate, and the weight placed on future versus immediate rewards is governed by a discount factor; a high discount factor makes the agent patient, and patience is precisely what makes cooperative pricing attractive, because cooperation trades a small immediate gain from undercutting for a larger stream of future profit.

A learning agent faces a fundamental tension between exploiting the actions it currently believes are best and exploring alternatives that might turn out to be better. This is handled by an epsilon-greedy policy: with some probability the agent picks a random price to keep learning about the environment, and otherwise it picks the price it currently believes is best. The exploration probability begins high, so the agent samples the full range of prices early on, and decays slowly toward a small floor as learning progresses, so that behaviour eventually settles. Decaying this probability too quickly is the single most common cause of failure, because an agent that stops exploring before it has properly learned the environment locks itself into a suboptimal pricing strategy. A second practical requirement is that rewards be rescaled to a moderate range before they enter the value updates, since raw profits of an arbitrary magnitude can cause the learned values either to grow without bound or to shrink into insignificance.

When such a learning agent is placed in the pricing market, its behaviour depends sharply on the rival it faces, and this dependence is the heart of the result. Against a rival that always competes at the Nash price, the learning agent has no way to be rewarded for raising its own price, since the rival will never reciprocate, and so it learns to price competitively, landing near the Nash benchmark with a collusion index close to zero. Against a rival capable of conditional cooperation, however, the learning agent discovers that charging higher prices is met with higher prices in return and that undercutting is punished, and so it learns to raise its prices, settling at an outcome partway between competition and collusion. It reaches this cooperative region without any communication, any explicit agreement, or any instruction to collude; it simply learns from experience that, against the right kind of opponent, restraint pays. This is the essential and somewhat unsettling finding that motivates the whole project: tacit collusion can emerge as the learned, profit-maximising behaviour of independent pricing algorithms, purely as a consequence of repeated interaction and the logic of reward and punishment, which raises difficult questions for competition policy in markets increasingly run by autonomous pricing systems.

Throughout, the analytically derived Nash and monopoly outcomes function as the fixed reference points against which everything is measured. Because they are computed exactly from the demand and cost primitives rather than estimated, they provide a correct ruler, and any error in them would silently distort every downstream conclusion, which is why they are established and verified before any environment or agent is constructed. The repeated-game structure provides the mechanism by which cooperation can survive, the rule-based strategies map out the landscape of possible outcomes, the collusion index turns that landscape into a single measurable quantity, and the learning agent demonstrates that a system designed only to maximise its own profit will navigate that landscape toward collusion whenever the strategic environment rewards it for doing so.
